 the system of campaign finance and to his own reputation as a reform candidate." (editorial, "(candidate last) opts out of reform," the boston globe, 6/20/08)</li></ul> <b><i>chyron:</i></b> "opportunistic and cynical." (new hampshire union leader, 6/20/08)<p></p><ul><li><b>new hampshire union leader:</b> "(candidate last)'s decision is entirely opportunistic and cynical." "of course, (candidate last)'s decision is entirely opportunistic and cynical. he claims he still believes in public financing, but that the current system, which he has championed all these years, he now thinks is so flawed that he cannot participate in it." (editorial, "(candidate last)'s financing: private beats public," new hampshire union leader, 6/20/08)</li></ul> <b><i>chyron:</i></b> "a large and telling (candidate last) flip-flop." (the wall street journal, 6/20/08)<p></p><ul><li><b>the wall street journal:</b> "the fact remains that the decision is a large and telling (candidate last) flip-flop." "is this the tone of the new postpartisan (candidate last) era? one may wonder. the fact remains that the decision is a large and telling (candidate last) flip-flop. he said early on that he would accept public financing for the general campaign, which runs between the conventions and november's vote. but this was back when he couldn't be sure he would be able to raise so much money by nonpublic means, or what he has since called his 'parallel' public financing system." (editorial, "a reformer's progress," the wall street journal, 6/20/08)</li></ul> <b><i>chyron:</i></b> "as disappointing as it is disingenuous." (the philadelphia inquirer, 6/20/08)<p></p><ul><li><b>philadelphia inquirer:</b> "(candidate full)'s decision to turn down public financing for the general election is a disappointing as it is disingenuous." "(candidate full)'s decision to turn down public financing for the general election is as disappointing as it is disingenuous. the presumptive (PARTY NAME) nominee for president pledged last year that he would accept public financing and its accompanying spending limits in the general election if his (PARTY NAME) foe did the same. but now that (candidate last) is a fund-raising sensation on the internet, he's breaking his pledge." (editorial, "public campaign financing," the philadelphia inquirer, 6/20/08)</li></ul></span>



